<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Speakie on Henry Techie</title><link>https://namanh11611.github.io/tags/speakie/</link><description>Recent content in Speakie on Henry Techie</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Sun, 11 May 2025 01:00:00 +0700</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://namanh11611.github.io/tags/speakie/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Applying LeetCode Algorithms to the Speakie English Learning App</title><link>https://namanh11611.github.io/p/speakie/</link><pubDate>Sun, 11 May 2025 01:00:00 +0700</pubDate><guid>https://namanh11611.github.io/p/speakie/</guid><description>&lt;img src="https://namanh11611.github.io/p/speakie/speakie.webp" alt="Featured image of post Applying LeetCode Algorithms to the Speakie English Learning App" />&lt;p>There&amp;rsquo;s a long-standing debate: &lt;em>&amp;ldquo;Is grinding algorithms only for &lt;strong>preparing for coding interviews&lt;/strong> and rarely &lt;strong>applicable to real work&lt;/strong>?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em> Of course, there are obvious examples like &lt;strong>ride-hailing apps&lt;/strong> that must use &lt;strong>pathfinding algorithms&lt;/strong>, a classic topic we&amp;rsquo;ve learned since university. But writing such important algorithms seems reserved for a &lt;strong>small group of senior developers&lt;/strong>, while most of us do simpler tasks and wonder when we&amp;rsquo;ll get to use the knowledge we&amp;rsquo;ve worked so hard to acquire. Are we &lt;strong>wasting a lot of time&lt;/strong>?&lt;/p>
&lt;p>So, today&amp;rsquo;s article shares a problem I encountered in a project, and how practicing &lt;strong>LeetCode&lt;/strong> helped me solve it. I&amp;rsquo;m not bragging—this is just a small algorithm, not something &lt;strong>world-changing&lt;/strong>. I just want to show: &lt;em>&amp;ldquo;Oh, so grinding algorithms can sometimes be applied to real projects like this&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em> 😜&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 id="the-problem">The Problem
&lt;/h1>&lt;p>I was building an English speaking app called &lt;a class="link" href="https://speakie.xyz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>&lt;strong>Speakie&lt;/strong>&lt;/a>, mainly to solve my own pain point: I couldn&amp;rsquo;t speak full sentences in conversation, often pausing to think about grammar. So, the lessons in the app are based on &lt;strong>common conversational sentence patterns&lt;/strong>.&lt;/p>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>Quick ad break:&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Android: &lt;a class="link" href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.areser.speakie" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.areser.speakie&lt;/a>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>iOS: &lt;a class="link" href="https://apps.apple.com/app/speakie/id6593695505" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>https://apps.apple.com/app/speakie/id6593695505&lt;/a>&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;p>The problem: When a user speaks a sentence, I need to compare it to the sample sentence, marking correct words in &lt;strong>green&lt;/strong> and incorrect words in &lt;strong>red&lt;/strong>. And I need to mark as many words green as possible to encourage the user.&lt;/p>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>Example:&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;strong>Sample sentence:&lt;/strong> Hello World! Welcome to my app Speakie.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;strong>User&amp;rsquo;s sentence:&lt;/strong> Hello Henry! Welcome to my world.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>==&amp;gt; In this case, the sample sentence would have &amp;ldquo;Hello&amp;rdquo;, &amp;ldquo;Welcome&amp;rdquo;, &amp;ldquo;to&amp;rdquo;, &amp;ldquo;my&amp;rdquo; marked green.&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;p>A naive solution is to use a &lt;code>Set&lt;/code> to store the words from the user&amp;rsquo;s sentence, then check each word in the sample sentence—if the &lt;code>Set&lt;/code> contains the word, mark it green; otherwise, mark it red. But this doesn&amp;rsquo;t preserve word order. For example, if &amp;ldquo;world&amp;rdquo; appears out of order, this method would still mark it green.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>While working, I noticed some popular English learning apps still make this mistake. You can test it by intentionally saying words out of order 😉&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 id="leetcode-problem">LeetCode problem
&lt;/h1>&lt;p>When thinking of a solution, I immediately remembered the &lt;a class="link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-common-subsequence" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Longest Common Subsequence&lt;/a> problem:&lt;/p>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>Given two strings &lt;code>text1&lt;/code> and &lt;code>text2&lt;/code>, return the length of their longest common subsequence. If there is no common subsequence, return 0.&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;h1 id="solution">Solution
&lt;/h1>&lt;p>The solution is to use dynamic programming (DP). We build a 2D array where &lt;code>dp[i][j]&lt;/code> represents the length of the longest common subsequence of &lt;code>text1[0..i-1]&lt;/code> and &lt;code>text2[0..j-1]&lt;/code>. The relationship is:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>If &lt;code>text1[i-1] == text2[j-1]&lt;/code>, then &lt;code>dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1&lt;/code>.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Otherwise, &lt;code>dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])&lt;/code>.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>The answer will be in &lt;code>dp[text1.length()][text2.length()]&lt;/code>.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="java-code">Java code
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>Here&amp;rsquo;s the Java code I implemented in the project:&lt;/p>
